'''Bertha of Cornouaille''' ([[floruit|fl.]] 1125-55), also known as '''Bertha of Brittany''' ({{lang-br|Berthe Breizh}}), was hereditary Duchess of [[Brittany]] between 1148 until her death and Dowager Countess of Richmond. Bertha was the eldest daughter of [[Conan III, Duke of Brittany|Conan III of Brittany]] by [[Matilda FitzRoy, Duchess of Brittany|Maude]], the [[illegitimate]] daughter of King [[Henry I of England]].{{sfn|Bryan|2016|p=173}} She was the last member of the Breton House of [[Cornouaille]] to reign over Brittany.

==Life==
Bertha was the daughter of [[Conan III of Brittany|Duke Conan III of Brittany]]. She married the son of Stephen of Treguier, [[Alan de Bretagne, 1st Earl of Richmond|Alan the Black]]{{sfn|Warren|1977|p=75}} and she lived in England with Alan until his death in 1146. Alan would eventually become Earl of Richmond. After Alan's death she returned to Brittany as Dowager Countess of Richmond and eventually married [[Odo, Viscount of Porhoet]]. When her father Duke Conan III died, on his deathbed Conan III renounced Bertha's brother [[Hoel, Count of Nantes|Hoèl]] as heir,{{sfn|Warren|1977|p=75}} and designated Bertha as his heiress. On Conan III's death she became hereditary Duchess of Brittany.{{sfn|Everard|2004|p=149}}

==Family==
In her first marriage, by 1138, Bertha was married to [[Alan de Bretagne, 1st Earl of Richmond|Alan le Noir]] {{efn|Alan le Noir was [[Counts and dukes of Penthièvre|Count of Penthièvre]]. He was created 1st [[Earl of Richmond]] by [[Stephen of England]] for his support against the dispossessed [[Empress Matilda]] during the English Civil War.<ref>Cokayne, G. E., edited by H. A. Doubleday, Geoffrey H. White, & Lord Howard de Walden, ''The Complete Peerage'', London, 1945, vol. x, p. 788.</ref> The marriage between Bertha and Alan may have been intended to bring Brittany into the English Civil War on the side of Stephen.}} 

Bertha and Alan had three children:
*[[Conan IV, Duke of Brittany]], b. 1138, their son and heir, as [[Duchy of Brittany|Duke of Brittany]] and [[Earl of Richmond]]{{sfn|Everard|2004|p=149}}
* [[Constance of Penthièvre|Constance]], who married Alan III, Viscount of [[House of Rohan|Rohan]]
* Enoguen, abbess of St. Sulpice

Bertha married her second husband, [[Odo, Viscount of Porhoet]] in about 1148.{{sfn|Warren|1977|p=75}}{{sfn|Everard|2004|p=32}} Bertha and Odo had three children:
* Geoffroy.
* Adelaide (died in 1220), Abbess of [[Abbaye de Fontevraud|Fontevrault]]
* Alix, mistress of [[Henry II, King of England]]

==Succession==
Bertha died between 1158 and 1164, and with her death the ducal throne passed to her son Conan. {{efn|War broke out between Bertha's son [[Conan IV, Duke of Brittany]] and her second husband Odo. Odo may have made a compact with his brother-in-law, Hoel of Nantes to divide Brittany between them. However in late 1156 Conan IV was able to defeat Odo and secure his maternal inheritance.}}

