'''David Duncombe''' (1802–1887) was a physician and political figure in [[Upper Canada]].
He was born in New York state in 1802 and came to Upper Canada with his brother [[Charles Duncombe (Upper Canada Rebellion)|Charles]]. He studied medicine at Fairfield College in New York state and later served as [[coroner]] in the [[Talbot District, Ontario|Talbot District]]. He was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Upper Canada]] to represent [[Norfolk County, Ontario|Norfolk]] in 1834 and served until 1841. He was a [[Reform Party (pre-Confederation)|Reformer]] but did not participate in the [[Upper Canada Rebellion]].
He died at [[Waterford, Ontario|Waterford]] in 1887.
== References == *{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=J. K.|title=Becoming Prominent: Regional Leadership in Upper Canada, 1791-1841|year=1989|publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press|location=Kingston|isbn=0-7735-0641-1}}
