{{Portal bar|Politics|United States}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:Politicians, List Of Assassinated American}} [[Category:Assassinated American politicians|*]] [[Category:Lists of American politicians|Assassinated American politicians]] [[Category:United States crime-related lists|Assassinated politicians]] [[Category:Lists of assassinations|American politicians]]

'''Morphological freedom''' refers to a proposed [[civil right]] of a [[person]] to either maintain or [[body modification|modify their own body]], on their own terms, through [[informed consent|informed, consensual]] recourse to, or refusal of, available therapeutic or enabling [[medical technology]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Bostrom | first1 = N. | title = In Defense of Posthuman Dignity | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-8519.2005.00437.x | journal = Bioethics | volume = 19 | issue = 3 | pages = 202–214 | year = 2005 | pmid =  16167401| pmc = }}</ref>

The term may have been coined by [[transhumanist]] [[Max More]] in his 1993 article, ''Technological Self-Transformation: Expanding Personal Extropy'', where he defined it as "the ability to alter bodily form at will through technologies such as surgery, genetic engineering, nanotechnology, uploading". The term was later used by science debater [[Anders Sandberg]] as "an extension of one’s right to one’s body, not just [[self-ownership]] but also the right to modify oneself according to one’s desires."<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Bradshaw | first1 = H. G. | last2 = Ter Meulen | first2 = R. | doi = 10.1093/jmp/jhq048 | title = A Transhumanist Fault Line Around Disability: Morphological Freedom and the Obligation to Enhance | journal = Journal of Medicine and Philosophy | volume = 35 | issue = 6 | pages = 670–684 | year = 2010 | pmid =  21076073| pmc = }}</ref>

==Politics==
According to [[technocritic]] [[Dale Carrico]], the politics of morphological freedom imply a commitment to the value, standing, and social legibility of the widest possible variety of desired [[morphology (biology)|morphologies]] and [[lifestyle (sociology)|lifestyle]]s. More specifically, morphological freedom is an expression of [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] [[Pluralism (political philosophy)|pluralism]], [[secularism]], [[progressivism|progressive]] [[cosmopolitanism]], and [[posthumanist]] [[multiculturalism]]s applied to the ongoing and upcoming transformation of the understanding of [[medicine|medical practice]] from one of conventional therapy to one of [[informed consent|consensual]] [[Self-Determination Theory|self-determination]], via [[human genetic engineering|genetic]], [[cyberware|prosthetic]], and [[neuropharmacology|cognitive]] modification.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}

==Religion==
According to authors Calvin Mercer and Tracy J. Trothen there is tension between religion and transhumanists, particularly the [[Abrahamic]] traditions, with regards to morphological freedom. While religion generally recognizes the need to heal people and improve their situation from a medical perspective they are generally hesitant to promote a wholesale modification of the body as they see it ultimately belonging to their god.<ref name="MercerTrothen2014">{{cite book|author1=Calvin Mercer|author2=Tracy J. Trothen|title=Religion and Transhumanism: The Unknown Future of Human Enhancement: The Unknown Future of Human Enhancement|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3GFhBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA303|pages=303 - 311|date=17 November 2014|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-4408-3326-7}}</ref>

